Written. The ADR makes a definitive recommendation for **Redis Streams** over Kafka, driven by the hard constraints that dominate this decision:

**Team of 6, no Kafka experience, no infra engineer, 2-week delivery window** — these rule out Kafka regardless of its technical merits. Redis Streams delivers the same core guarantees (async dispatch, consumer groups, retry, at-least-once) using infrastructure already in production, with the team already familiar with its operational profile.

The exactly-once requirement for billing is handled at the **consumer layer** via `event_id` deduplication — the industry-standard approach regardless of broker choice, since true end-to-end exactly-once requires idempotent consumers anyway.

Kafka is flagged as a future re-evaluation point when throughput exceeds 50k msg/s or multi-month event sourcing becomes necessary.
